Dependency injection is a design pattern that helps to decouple the objects in a program from their dependencies. It involves passing the dependencies into the objects at runtime, rather than hard-coding them.

Here's an example of how dependency injection works in C#:

Imagine you have a class called "Car", which requires a "Wheel" object to function properly. In a typical programming approach, you would create the "Car" class and hard-code the "Wheel" object into its constructor:

```c#
public class Car
{
    private readonly Wheel wheel;

    public Car(Wheel wheel)
    {
        this.wheel = wheel;
    }
}
```

However, this approach can be problematic if the "Wheel" object changes or if you need to use a different type of wheel, such as a "Tire."

With dependency injection, you could create an interface called "IWheel" and have the "Car" class depend on it:

```c#
public interface IWheel
{
    // Define the properties and methods of the wheel
}
```

Then, you could create a "Tire" class that implements the "IWheel" interface:

```c#
public class Tire : IWheel
{
    // Implement the methods and properties of the wheel
}
```

When you instantiate the "Car" object, instead of passing in a "Wheel" object, you would pass in an "IWheel" object:

```c#
public class Car
{
    private readonly IWheel wheel;

    public Car(IWheel wheel)
    {
        this.wheel = wheel;
    }
}
```

Now, you can use the "Car" object with either a "Wheel" or a "Tire," depending on what you need. This allows you to decouple the "Car" object from its dependencies, making it more flexible and easier to maintain.

Overall, dependency injection is a powerful design pattern that can help you create more maintainable and flexible code.

